\f0\b\fs36 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 GPT5.4, Gemini3.1, ClaudeOpus4.6 and 4xA100 GPUs!\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 LLM tools are so exciting! All of this solution's code was written by GPT5.4, Gemini3.1, ClaudeOpus4.6 and experimentation was accelerated with GPU, Nvidia cuDF, and Nvidia cuML. These agents learned to understand and follow the KGMON Playbook for tabular data and finish 1st place!\cb1 \
\cb3 In the month of March 2026, these LLMs wrote 600,000 lines of code! They built and trained 850 models on 4xA100 GPU and wrote and ran 50 EDA scripts! Wow unbelievable!\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 1. Final Solution - Four Level GBDT NN Stack\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 Our final solution is a 4 level stack. The first level is feature extraction models like Nvidia cuML KNN, PyTorch Denoising Auto encoder, PCA clustering, Nvidia cuML Target Encoding, etc etc. These models aggregate information from other rows to augment the current row. The second level is many GBDT and NN using 5x5 nested OOF from level 1. The third level is many GBDT and NN using 5x5 nested OOF from level 2. The fourth and final level is Nvidia cuML Logistic Regression using OOF from level 3 and level 2.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf7 {{\NeXTGraphic 4LevelStack.png \width20460 \height11520 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}洞\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf7 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf7 \cb3 Besides the benefit of a large deep stack, the secret sauce involved creating 850 diverse potential models to select a final 150 models from. And the secret sauce involved creating 100s of diverse feature engineering techniques. Below we summarize our models and feature engineering. Many ideas were taken from public notebooks and references are provided at the end of the write up.\cb1 \
\cb3 In addition to building models, GPT5.4, Gemini3.1, ClaudeOpus4.6 were prompted to perform their own EDA to determine the relationship between\'a0
\f2 \cb8 train.csv 600k row synthetic data
\f1 \cb3 \'a0and\'a0
\f2 \cb8 7k original data
\f1 \cb3 \'a0and\'a0
\f2 \cb8 train.csv targets
\f1 \cb3 . Then they used their discoveries to create many new feature engineering ideas to extract signal.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 2. Feature Engineering\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 Feature engineering was the dominant driver of performance. Nearly all 150 models share a common core, with different models exploring additional specialized techniques.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 2.1 Snap Features (universal)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 Map each synthetic float to its nearest value in the original IBM dataset:\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2 \cf9 \cb8 \strokec9 MC_snap      = nearest MonthlyCharges in original IBM data\
TC_snap      = nearest TotalCharges in original IBM data\
MC_snap_diff = MonthlyCharges - MC_snap   \cf10 \strokec10 # synthetic noise\cf9 \strokec9 \
TC_snap_diff = TotalCharges  - TC_snap\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf7 \cb1 \strokec7 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1 \cf7 \cb3 Used in nearly every model. The snap value recovers the "true" original feature; the diff encodes the generator's perturbation magnitude.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 2.2 Digit and Decimal Extraction (~60 models)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 The most pervasive technique. Extract the digit at every decimal position:\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2 \cf9 \cb8 \strokec9 frac    = x - floor(x)\
d1      = floor(frac * \cf11 \strokec11 10\cf9 \strokec9 )         \cf10 \strokec10 # 1st decimal digit\cf9 \strokec9 \
d2      = floor(frac * \cf11 \strokec11 100\cf9 \strokec9 ) % \cf11 \strokec11 10\cf9 \strokec9    \cf10 \strokec10 # 2nd decimal digit\cf9 \strokec9 \
frac100 = round(frac * \cf11 \strokec11 100\cf9 \strokec9 )        \cf10 \strokec10 # 2-digit integer representation\cf9 \strokec9 \
mod10   = floor(x) % \cf11 \strokec11 10\cf9 \strokec9 \
mod100  = floor(x) % \cf11 \strokec11 100\cf9 \strokec9 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf7 \cb1 \strokec7 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1 \cf7 \cb3 Applied to raw\'a0
\f2 \cb8 MonthlyCharges
\f1 \cb3 ,\'a0
\f2 \cb8 TotalCharges
\f1 \cb3 , and their snap values. Also: fractional residuals from common denominators (1/2, 1/4, 1/5, 1/10), is-round flags (
\f2 \cb8 frac < 0.005
\f1 \cb3 ), and digit pair combinations as categorical strings.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 2.3 Target Encoding \'97 Nested / Leak-Free (~90 models)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 All target encoding (TE) uses a nested inner 5-fold loop within each outer CV fold to prevent label leakage:\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa160\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0\cf7 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec7 Applied to: all 16 raw categorical columns, bigram/trigram combos, binned numerics, anchor keys, and numeric \'d7 categorical snap products\cb1 \
\ls2\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec7 TE statistics beyond the mean: std, min, max, median, quantiles (5th, 10th, 45th, 55th, 90th, 95th)\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa160\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf7 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec7 Original IBM priors
\f1\b0 : churn probability per feature value computed once from the 7,032-row original dataset \'97 zero leakage, as the original data carries no synthetic training labels\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 2.4 Arithmetic Interactions (~45 models)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs28 \cf9 \cb8 \strokec9 TC_deviation     = TotalCharges - tenure * MonthlyCharges\
TC_snap_exp_dev  = TC_snap - tenure * MC_snap   \cf10 \strokec10 # original billing anomaly\cf9 \strokec9 \
TC_per_month     = TotalCharges / (tenure + \cf11 \strokec11 1\cf9 \strokec9 )\
MC_to_TC_ratio   = MonthlyCharges / (TotalCharges + \cf11 \strokec11 1\cf9 \strokec9 e-\cf11 \strokec11 9\cf9 \strokec9 )\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf7 \cb1 \strokec7 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf7 \cb8 TC_deviation
\f1 \cb3 \'a0is particularly powerful \'97 it captures how much a customer's actual total charges deviate from what their monthly charge and tenure would predict.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 2.5 Multi-Scale Binning (~52 models)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 Quantile bins (up to 5,000 bins), fixed-width bins, log-scale bins, and integer floor \'97 all converted to categorical strings and then target-encoded. Fine-grained quantile bins on\'a0
\f2 \cb8 MonthlyCharges
\f1 \cb3 \'a0(5,000 bins) essentially recover the original 1,584 unique values.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 2.6 Categorical Cross-Features / Bigrams (~37 models)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs28 \cf11 \cb8 \strokec11 df\cf9 \strokec9 [\cf12 \strokec12 "bi_Contract_Internet"\cf9 \strokec9 ] = \cf11 \strokec11 df\cf9 \strokec9 [\cf12 \strokec12 "Contract"\cf9 \strokec9 ] + \cf12 \strokec12 "__"\cf9 \strokec9  + \cf11 \strokec11 df\cf9 \strokec9 [\cf12 \strokec12 "InternetService"\cf9 \strokec9 ]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf7 \cb1 \strokec7 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1 \cf7 \cb3 Top-signal pairs:\'a0
\f2 \cb8 Contract \'d7 InternetService
\f1 \cb3 ,\'a0
\f2 \cb8 Contract \'d7 PaymentMethod
\f1 \cb3 ,\'a0
\f2 \cb8 InternetService \'d7 PaymentMethod
\f1 \cb3 . Trigrams extend this to 3-way combinations. Nested TE on these combos captures joint churn profiles unavailable to per-column TE.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 2.7 Frequency / Count Encoding (~45 models)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs28 \cf9 \cb8 \strokec9 freq = all_data[col]\cf13 \strokec13 .value_counts\cf9 \strokec9 (normalize=True)\
all_data[f\cf12 \strokec12 "freq_\{col\}"\cf9 \strokec9 ] = all_data[col]\cf13 \strokec13 .map\cf9 \strokec9 (freq)\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf7 \cb1 \strokec7 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1 \cf7 \cb3 Especially powerful for\'a0
\f2 \cb8 MC_snap
\f1 \cb3 \'a0(1,584 unique values): the frequency encodes how many synthetic rows cluster around each original IBM value, which correlates with the original customer's representativeness. Count ratio features (
\f2 \cb8 synthetic_count / original_count
\f1 \cb3 ) measure how much the generator oversampled each value.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 2.8 Service Count Aggregations (~30 models)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs28 \cf14 \cb8 \strokec14 svc_cols\cf9 \strokec9  = [\cf12 \strokec12 "OnlineSecurity"\cf9 \strokec9 ,\cf12 \strokec12 "OnlineBackup"\cf9 \strokec9 ,\cf12 \strokec12 "DeviceProtection"\cf9 \strokec9 ,\
            \cf12 \strokec12 "TechSupport"\cf9 \strokec9 ,\cf12 \strokec12 "StreamingTV"\cf9 \strokec9 ,\cf12 \strokec12 "StreamingMovies"\cf9 \strokec9 ,\cf12 \strokec12 "MultipleLines"\cf9 \strokec9 ]\
\cf14 \strokec14 svc_yes\cf9 \strokec9  = sum((df[c]==\cf12 \strokec12 "Yes"\cf9 \strokec9 ).\cf15 \strokec15 astype\cf9 \strokec9 (int) for c in svc_cols)\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf7 \cb1 \strokec7 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1 \cf7 \cb3 Also:\'a0
\f2 \cb8 has_internet
\f1 \cb3 ,\'a0
\f2 \cb8 has_phone
\f1 \cb3 , per-service binary flags (
\f2 \cb8 ISYES_
\f1 \cb3 ,\'a0
\f2 \cb8 ISNO_
\f1 \cb3 ,\'a0
\f2 \cb8 ISOTHER_
\f1 \cb3 ).\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 2.9 Original IBM Dataset Lookup (~7 models)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 Build a\'a0
\f2 \cb8 cKDTree
\f1 \cb3 \'a0on the standardized\'a0
\f2 \cb8 (MonthlyCharges, TotalCharges, tenure)
\f1 \cb3 \'a0columns of the 7,032 original IBM rows. For each synthetic row, find the nearest original customer and attach their churn label as a feature. This provides a zero-leakage, noise-free "ground truth" anchor.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 2.10 Radix Interaction Features (~15 models)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs28 \cf16 \cb8 \strokec16 radix\cf9 \strokec9  = int(MC_snap * \cf11 \strokec11 100\cf9 \strokec9 ) + cat_code * \cf11 \strokec11 100\cf9 \strokec9 _000\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf7 \cb1 \strokec7 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1 \cf7 \cb3 Encodes a (continuous, categorical) pair as a single integer category. Very natural for tree models: a single split on this integer is equivalent to splitting on both the numeric value and the categorical value simultaneously.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 2.11 Synthetic Artifact Detection (specialized)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 Several models go further in exploiting the generator's fingerprints:\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa160\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf7 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec7 Fractional fingerprints
\f1\b0 :\'a0
\f2 \cb8 intlike_count
\f1 \cb3 \'a0(frac < 0.001),\'a0
\f2 \cb8 quarterlike_count
\f1 \cb3 ,\'a0
\f2 \cb8 halflike_count
\f1 \cb3 \'a0\'97 how many of a row's numeric values look like round numbers\cb1 \
\ls3\ilvl0
