\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 3.4 YDF (Yggdrasil Decision Forests) \'97 2 Models\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 Google's YDF with\'a0
\f2 \cb8 max_depth=2
\f1 \cb3 \'a0produces ultra-shallow stumps \'97 extremely regularized, smooth prediction surfaces that are almost orthogonal to the deep-tree models. Its value is purely ensemble diversity.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf17 \strokec17 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 3.5 Nvidia cuML Random Forest \'97 2 Models\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 RAPIDS cuML's GPU-accelerated Random Forest provides the only\'a0
\f0\b bagging
\f1\b0 \'a0ensemble in the tree family \'97 all other tree models use boosting. Because bagging averages many independently-grown deep trees rather than greedily correcting residuals, the cuML RF produces a fundamentally different prediction surface that adds genuine diversity to the boosted-tree bloc.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 4. Deep Learning Models\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 60 of the 150 models are neural networks, spanning 25 distinct architecture families. All use PyTorch (directly or via\'a0
\f2 \cb8 pytabkit
\f1 \cb3 \'a0/\'a0
\f2 \cb8 pytorch-tabular
\f1 \cb3 \'a0/\'a0
\f2 \cb8 pytorch-frame
\f1 \cb3 ) with CUDA acceleration.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 4.1 Embedding MLP \'97 Standard PyTorch (10 models)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 The foundational DL architecture: learned categorical embeddings (dimension \uc0\u8776  \u8730 cardinality) concatenated with raw numerics, passed through a 2\'963 layer MLP (512
\f4 \uc0\u8594 
\f1 256
\f4 \uc0\u8594 
\f1 1) with dropout and BatchNorm/LayerNorm. Seven variants explore diverse training configurations (batch size 256\'968192, LR 2.5e-5\'962e-3, cosine annealing, label smoothing \uc0\u949 =0.02) to maximize prediction diversity.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 4.2 Feature Interaction MLP \'97 Pair Embeddings (2 models)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 Every ordered pair of the 19 input features gets its own embedding table (171 pairs, dim capped at 16), then all pair embeddings are concatenated and passed through a 3-layer MLP. Explicitly models every second-order feature interaction as a learnable embedding rather than relying on MLP hidden layers to discover them implicitly.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 4.3 Enhanced Feature MLP \'97 XGB-Inspired Transforms (4 models)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 Same Embedding MLP backbone but numerical features are enriched with five transforms borrowed from gradient boosting practice: frequency encoding (FREQ), rank transform (RANK), log1p, square-root (SQRT), and reciprocal (INV1P), all standardized. Bridges the gap between tree-based and neural approaches by giving the MLP pre-processed numerical representations that mimic the decision boundaries trees naturally find.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 4.4 RealMLP \'97 pytabkit (9 models)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 RealMLP_TD_Classifier
\f1 \cb3 \'a0from the\'a0
\f2 \cb8 pytabkit
\f1 \cb3 \'a0library. Key innovations: piecewise-linear representations (PLR) for numerical features (bin-then-learn approach giving quasi-tree-like inductive bias), SiLU activations, L2 normalization, robust scaling, label smoothing, flat+cosine LR schedule, and an 8-member internal ensemble baked into each fit (
\f2 \cb8 n_ens=8
\f1 \cb3 ). One of the strongest individual architectures.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 4.5 GraphSAGE GNN (4 models)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 Each training/test row becomes a graph node; a KNN graph (k=8, built via cuML GPU-accelerated KNN) connects each customer to its nearest neighbors in feature space. Two SAGEConv layers aggregate neighbor information before an MLP classification head. Allows each customer's predicted churn probability to be informed by the churn patterns of their k nearest similar customers \'97 a structural inductive bias unavailable to any MLP.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 4.6 FT-Transformer (4 models)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 Each input feature (numerical or categorical) is tokenized into a fixed-dimension embedding, then a Transformer encoder (multi-head self-attention + FFN) processes the sequence of feature tokens. A\'a0
\f2 \cb8 [CLS]
\f1 \cb3 \'a0token is used for classification. Self-attention among feature tokens allows every feature to attend to every other feature at each layer, learning arbitrary high-order interactions. Implemented via\'a0
\f2 \cb8 pytorch-frame
\f1 \cb3 's\'a0
\f2 \cb8 FTTransformer
\f1 \cb3 \'a0with\'a0
\f2 \cb8 LinearPeriodicEncoder
\f1 \cb3 \'a0for numericals.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 4.7 TabTransformer (5 models)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 Applies Transformer self-attention exclusively to categorical feature embeddings, then concatenates context-aware categorical embeddings with layer-normalized numerics and passes through an MLP head. The hypothesis: categorical relationships (e.g., Contract type vs. InternetService) benefit most from attention, while numeric correlations are better left to the MLP.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 4.8 TabM \'97 Multiplicative Interactions (3 models)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 TabM_D_Classifier
\f1 \cb3 \'a0from\'a0
\f2 \cb8 pytabkit
\f1 \cb3 \'a0with\'a0
\f2 \cb8 tabm-mini-normal
\f1 \cb3 \'a0architecture: PLR embeddings for numerics, MLP blocks with multiplicative (bilinear) interactions alongside additive paths, and\'a0
\f2 \cb8 k=32
\f1 \cb3 \'a0basis components linearly combined per sample. The implicit ensemble effect from k-component basis decomposition makes TabM one of the strongest individual DL models (OOF AUC\'a0
\f0\b 0.918788
\f1\b0 ).\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 4.9 TabICL \'97 In-Context Learning (3 models)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 TabICLClassifier
\f1 \cb3 \'a0from the\'a0
\f2 \cb8 tabicl
\f1 \cb3 \'a0library is a Transformer-based foundation model pre-trained on thousands of tabular datasets. At inference time it takes the training set as context and predicts test row labels by attending over training examples \'97 zero fine-tuning required. The only model in the ensemble that requires no gradient updates at all.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 4.10 GANDALF (2 model)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 From\'a0
\f2 \cb8 pytorch-tabular
\f1 \cb3 : Gated Feature Learning Units (GFLU) gate inputs with learned sigmoid masks, select top-K most relevant features, and apply learned transformations across multiple stages. The multi-stage gating progressively filters the feature set rather than relying on a monolithic weight matrix.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 4.11 Self-Normalizing Network \'97 SELU (2 model)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 Deep MLP (256
\f4 \uc0\u8594 
\f1 128
\f4 \uc0\u8594 
\f1 64
\f4 \uc0\u8594 
\f1 32) with SELU activations and AlphaDropout, maintaining mean\uc0\u8776 0 and variance\u8776 1 at every layer without explicit normalization. Uniquely also treats numeric values as text: TF-IDF character n-gram features (128-dim) extracted from the string representations of\'a0
\f2 \cb8 MonthlyCharges
\f1 \cb3 \'a0and\'a0
\f2 \cb8 TotalCharges
\f1 \cb3 , plus Benford's Law likelihood features.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 4.12 Tabular ResNet (2 model)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 ResNet-style MLP (4 residual blocks, pre-activation BatchNorm
\f4 \uc0\u8594 
\f1 ReLU
\f4 \uc0\u8594 
\f1 Linear
\f4 \uc0\u8594 
\f1 Dropout
\f4 \uc0\u8594 
\f1 Linear + skip) combined with manifold projection features (PCA + GRP fitted on original IBM data) and cyclical tenure features (sin/cos with periods 12 and 24 months).\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 4.13 RFF Kernel Network (3 models)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 Numerics are transformed via Random Fourier Features (RFF, dim=1,024) to approximate an RBF kernel, then concatenated with categorical embeddings and k=32 K-Means prototype distances fitted on original IBM data, and passed through an MLP. RFF projection explicitly maps inputs into a space where a linear classifier approximates a kernel SVM with RBF kernel.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 4.14 Denoising Autoencoder (DAE) (10 models)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 A PyTorch encoder-decoder (hidden 128
\f4 \uc0\u8594 
\f1 16 latent) trained exclusively on the 7,032-row original IBM dataset to reconstruct input features corrupted with Gaussian noise; reconstruction errors and latent embeddings computed on synthetic rows measure each row's deviation from the true IBM data manifold, which are then fed as features into XGBoost. The most powerful variant (dae-8907) combined DAE-derived features with a union of the strongest XGBoost feature sets, reaching\'a0
\f0\b 0.918345
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 matching the best individual models in the ensemble.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 4.15 Field-Aware Factorization Machine (FFM) (10 models)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 Extends the standard FM by learning field-specific factor vectors: feature i has a separate embedding\'a0
\f2 \cb8 v_\{i
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f2 j\}
\f1 \cb3 \'a0for every target field j, so pairwise interactions are computed with context-aware representations rather than a single global vector per feature. Competitive at ~0.9159 without any deep MLP branch.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 4.16 Deep Residual MLP (ResNet) (4 models)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 A 4-block residual MLP (hidden=512, BatchNorm
\f4 \uc0\u8594 
\f1 GELU
\f4 \uc0\u8594 
\f1 Linear + skip connection) with categorical embeddings scaled as 1.6\'d7\uc0\u8730 cardinality; uniquely augments each training fold with the original IBM rows so the model sees ground-truth customer archetypes directly alongside synthetic training examples. Reached 0.916376.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 4.17 Factorization Machine (FM) (3 models)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 A pure FM with no deep branch, modeling all pairwise feature interactions as\'a0
\f2 \cb8 <v_i, v_j>\'b7x_i\'b7x_j
\f1 \cb3 \'a0with factor dimension k=32 \'97 the simplest non-linear model in the experiment suite beyond logistic regression, competitive at 0.9155 purely from second-order interactions with no hidden layers. Serves as a useful lower bound showing how much signal is captured by pairwise interactions alone.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 4.18 DeepFM / DeepFFM (3 models)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 Combines an FM or FFM interaction component with a parallel deep MLP branch sharing the same embeddings; the two paths (FM pairwise terms + MLP higher-order terms) add their logits at the output. The deep branch adds higher-order interactions beyond the second-order FM terms and slightly exceeds the pure FM (0.9154\'960.9158).\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 4.19 Liquid Neural Networks (LNN) (3 models)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 Inspired by the C. elegans connectome: each neuron has a learnable time-constant parameter\'a0
\f5 \cb8 \uc0\u964 
\f1 \cb3 \'a0controlling state-decay dynamics, giving the network an ODE-like continuous-time structure even on static tabular inputs. The embedding variant (lnn-4401, hidden=384, 4 layers, 0.9151) outperformed the plain variant (lnn-4400, 0.9128).\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 4.20 Variable Selection Network (VSN / TFT-style) (4 models)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 Implements the Variable Selection Network from the Temporal Fusion Transformer (TFT) paper using Gated Linear Units (GLU) and Gated Residual Networks (GRN): each feature passes through a dedicated GRN, and outputs are recombined via learned softmax attention weights providing explicit feature importances. The best variant (G-10202) adds frequency snapping \'97 collapsing rare continuous values to the nearest frequent value before embedding \'97 to reach 0.9141, below most MLP variants of similar complexity.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 4.21 TabNet (3 models)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 Sequential sparse attention: at each decision step a learned mask selects a subset of features to process, conditioned on the aggregated representation from all prior steps, with the summed masks yielding interpretable feature importances. Both variants use self-supervised pre-training on augmented original IBM data before supervised fine-tuning via\'a0
\f2 \cb8 pytorch-tabnet
\f1 \cb3 's\'a0
\f2 \cb8 TabNetPretrainer
\f1 \cb3 \'a0topping out at ~0.9122.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 4.22 Trompt (PyTorch Frame) (3 models)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 A prompt-based tabular model from the\'a0
\f2 \cb8 torch_frame
\f1 \cb3 \'a0library that maintains\'a0
\f2 \cb8 num_prompts=8
\f1 \cb3 \'a0parallel context vectors through\'a0
\f2 \cb8 num_layers=4
\f1 \cb3 \'a0processing stages, applying cross-entropy loss independently at every layer (layer-wise supervision) and averaging layer predictions at inference \'97 adapting the prompting paradigm from NLP to tabular data. Reached\'a0
\f0\b 0.916291
\f1\b0 \'a0with minimal feature engineering (no target encoding, no digit features) and only 6 training epochs, still improving at the final epoch.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 4.23 DANet \'97 Deep Abstract Network (1 model)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 Within the FT-Transformer notebook: Abstract Layers select sparse subsets of input features via learnable attention masks, apply shared linear transforms to selected features, and stack multiple layers to progressively build higher-order representations. A differentiable feature-interaction filter inspired by tree splits.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 4.24 TabPFN v2.6 Foundation Model (1 model)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 A prior-data fitted Transformer trained offline on millions of synthetic tabular datasets that performs in-context learning at inference: the training set is passed as context and test row labels are predicted via attention over training examples, requiring zero gradient updates on the target data. At this dataset scale (475k training rows), the model must subsample to 5k\'9610k rows per estimator due to context-length limits \'97 with 32 estimators at 10k rows each outperforming 64 estimators at 5k rows (0.9134 vs. 0.9127) \'97 capping performance well below what full-dataset models achieve.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 4.25 DAE Transfer Learning (2 models)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 Two-phase training: a denoising autoencoder (110
\f4 \uc0\u8594 
\f1 64
\f4 \uc0\u8594 
\f1 32, corrupting 30% of features with swap noise and Gaussian noise) is first pre-trained unsupervised on the combined train+test set, then a lightweight classification head is attached to the frozen encoder and fine-tuned with supervised labels \'97 standard self-supervised transfer learning applied to tabular data. The 32-dimensional bottleneck learned a compressed representation of the full feature space, but the supervised fine-tuning phase could not exceed 0.915 despite the pre-training advantage.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 5. Stacking and Ensembling\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 Meta-learner\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 All 150 base model OOF predictions are combined via a\'a0
\f0\b Nvidia cuML L2-penalized Logistic Regression
\f1\b0 \'a0(logit stacking) fit on the training labels. The L2 penalty prevents any single model from dominating the stack and naturally handles the high correlation among similar models.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Second-layer stacking\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 Several models (
\f2 \cb8 _stk
\f1 \cb3 \'a0suffix) are themselves trained on OOF predictions from earlier models as additional input features \'97 creating a two-level hierarchy: raw feature models 
\f4 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  stacked models 
\f4 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  final logit meta-learner.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Diversity strategy\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 Diversity was intentional and systematic. The 150 models span:\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa160\partightenfactor0
\ls7\ilvl0\cf7 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec7 4 GBDT libraries with fundamentally different tree structures\cb1 \
\ls7\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec7 25 DL architecture families across attention, graph, kernel, multiplicative, gated, and foundation model paradigms\cb1 \
\ls7\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec7 12+ distinct feature engineering pipelines (anchor TE, digit features, radix interactions, survival analysis, TF-IDF on numerics, KDTree lookup, pairwise embeddings, etc.)\cb1 \
\ls7\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec7 Multiple random seeds and Optuna-tuned hyperparameter configs\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf7 \cb3 The logit stacker learns which model to trust for which region of the feature space.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

